WEBVTT

00:03.351 --> 00:05.048
RUDDY: Lenny was a little
on edge today.

00:05.092 --> 00:06.702
He was saying something
about Joe Gallo.

00:06.745 --> 00:08.878
Are you worried about me?Yeah, maybe.

00:13.100 --> 00:14.753
How is he?I don't know.

00:14.797 --> 00:16.712
I'm gonna go see him
at the hospital later.

00:16.755 --> 00:18.844
Do you really think
you should be doing that?

00:18.888 --> 00:21.673
No. I can't not go.

00:21.717 --> 00:23.023
BOB:
Look, we got a problem.

00:23.066 --> 00:25.373
Bluhdorn and Lapidus
saw dailies

00:25.416 --> 00:27.679
of Pacino's first day,
and they want to fire him.

00:27.723 --> 00:29.681
Barry's a fucking rat
who's always wanted my job,

00:29.725 --> 00:31.205
and this is part
of his power grab.

00:31.248 --> 00:33.033
I'm Joe Gallo,

00:33.076 --> 00:34.599
and I'm in charge
of your movie now.

00:34.643 --> 00:37.602
Whatever you were giving
Colombo, you now give to me.

00:37.646 --> 00:39.213
Fuck Sicily.

00:39.256 --> 00:40.953
Give Gallo the money.

00:40.997 --> 00:42.520
FRANCIS: Without Sicily,
it doesn't live or breathe.

00:42.564 --> 00:43.695
I'm begging you.

00:43.739 --> 00:46.568
I can't find the money.

00:46.611 --> 00:48.178
I don't know
what's going on with you

00:48.222 --> 00:49.745
or you and Ali
or whatever happened to you--

00:49.788 --> 00:51.790
My marriage is none
of your fucking business.

00:51.834 --> 00:53.270
Ever since then, you haven't
been the Bob Evans I know.

00:53.314 --> 00:54.793
[Bob snorting]

00:54.837 --> 00:56.317
[glass shatters]

01:01.974 --> 01:03.802
Joe Colombo says goodbye,
fuckhead.

01:03.846 --> 01:05.543
[spits]

01:05.587 --> 01:07.719
You can cross one thing
off your list.

01:07.763 --> 01:08.851
You don't have to worry

01:08.894 --> 01:10.113
about that
fucking psychopath anymore.

01:10.157 --> 01:12.376
We're going to Sicily, baby.

01:12.420 --> 01:15.031
We're going.You son of a bitch!

01:15.075 --> 01:17.947
[soft dramatic music]

01:17.990 --> 01:24.910
♪

01:26.521 --> 01:29.437
[upbeat dramatic music]

01:29.480 --> 01:36.183
♪

02:48.733 --> 02:51.519
♪ [Dik Dik's
"Sognando La California"]

02:51.562 --> 02:55.218
♪

02:55.262 --> 02:56.219
Grazie.

02:56.263 --> 02:59.222
[singing in Italian]

02:59.266 --> 03:02.486
♪

03:02.530 --> 03:04.793
Okay, we should be
getting close to Corleone.

03:04.836 --> 03:06.490
How many more miles?

03:06.534 --> 03:08.840
I don't know.
It's in kilometers.

03:08.884 --> 03:10.799
You used to work at Rand.

03:10.842 --> 03:13.149
You can't convert that?

03:13.193 --> 03:15.238
We're a half inch away.
How's that?

03:15.282 --> 03:17.501
[scoffs, chuckles]

03:17.545 --> 03:19.242
You know what my grandfather,
Francesco Penino,

03:19.286 --> 03:20.896
once told me about Italy?

03:20.939 --> 03:23.942
[sighs]
I bet we're gonna find out.

03:23.986 --> 03:26.118
He was a composer.

03:26.162 --> 03:29.034
And he told me that
when he emigrated to America

03:29.078 --> 03:30.558
that he missed home
like crazy.

03:30.601 --> 03:33.125
And when he finally
got to come back,

03:33.169 --> 03:35.867
it was like picking up
an old, beloved instrument

03:35.911 --> 03:37.782
that he hadn't played
in a really long time.

03:37.826 --> 03:39.697
Yeah, at first it was
a little out of tune,

03:39.741 --> 03:42.222
but then
when he started playing it,

03:42.265 --> 03:44.963
all the notes became
familiar again.

03:46.400 --> 03:49.359
For me, it's like I'm--

03:49.403 --> 03:52.275
I'm hearing these notes
for the first time.

03:52.319 --> 03:55.974
♪

03:56.018 --> 03:58.934
[singing in Italian]

03:58.977 --> 04:05.897
♪

04:17.953 --> 04:21.696
[indistinct music
playing over speakers]

04:26.309 --> 04:28.311
Would've been nice
to take a shower.

04:28.355 --> 04:30.400
Well, our Italian AD
said to meet him here,

04:30.444 --> 04:31.923
so we may as well eat.

04:31.967 --> 04:34.186
Okay.

04:34.230 --> 04:35.927
My friends, ciao!

04:35.971 --> 04:39.409
You must be Tony.Yes, I'm your AD.

04:39.453 --> 04:41.237
I'm Al.
This is the gang.

04:41.281 --> 04:42.543
Oh, my God, che bello.

04:42.586 --> 04:44.196
What a beautiful group
on a beautiful day.

04:44.240 --> 04:45.850
You came on the right day,
because it's today.

04:45.894 --> 04:47.287
Okay, you guys want
anti-pasta?

04:47.330 --> 04:48.810
RUDDY:
Grazie, grazie.

04:48.853 --> 04:50.899
[speaking Italian]

04:50.942 --> 04:52.466
BETTYE: Wow!Whatever you like, please.

04:52.509 --> 04:55.469
Exactly how I pictured it.TONY: I take as a compliment.

04:55.512 --> 04:56.992
BETTYE: Table for kings.
Look at this.

04:57.035 --> 04:59.299
Mr. Coppola, sit.

04:59.342 --> 05:00.517
[speaking Italian]
Nice to meet you.

05:00.561 --> 05:01.823
Yeah.

05:01.866 --> 05:02.911
Thank you so much.All right, please.

05:02.954 --> 05:04.260
Wow.

05:04.304 --> 05:05.827
Can't believe
we're actually here.

05:05.870 --> 05:07.132
I know. Don't jinx it.

05:09.221 --> 05:12.355
Hey, have you heard at all
from Evans?

05:12.399 --> 05:14.618
Since the circus act
he pulled at the wrap party?

05:14.662 --> 05:16.881
No, I haven't.Mm.

05:16.925 --> 05:19.493
You gonna call him?

05:19.536 --> 05:21.669
Have some eggplant, Bettye.
You look hungry.

05:21.712 --> 05:26.108
So how are you planning
to light the exteriors?

05:26.151 --> 05:28.893
You know that big ball
of burning plasma in the sky?

05:28.937 --> 05:30.721
No. Oh, the--the sun?

05:30.765 --> 05:32.810
Yeah, that's the one.

05:32.854 --> 05:34.290
Yeah, go fuck yourself.

05:34.334 --> 05:36.161
This Anisette,
this is so smooth.

05:36.205 --> 05:38.076
Al, what do you think?Oh, it's fantastic.

05:39.034 --> 05:41.863
Scusi,how do you make it?

05:41.906 --> 05:45.127
Um, come si prepare?

05:45.170 --> 05:47.869
Eh, local secret.[chuckles]

05:47.912 --> 05:49.871
Um, I make my own,

05:49.914 --> 05:53.788
but this--I--when I'm--

05:53.831 --> 05:55.964
[laughter]

05:56.007 --> 05:57.400
RUDDY: I think he--
I think he likes you.

05:57.444 --> 05:59.750
[laughter]

05:59.794 --> 06:02.449
Al, Al, let me introduce you
to our friend, Bruno.

06:02.492 --> 06:04.842
Oh, okay.Excuse me, excuse me.

06:04.886 --> 06:06.453
This is Bruno, okay.

06:06.496 --> 06:09.020
Now, he's made sure
everything will go smoothly,

06:09.064 --> 06:11.501
and he's assured us that
no permits will be necessary.

06:11.545 --> 06:13.590
Oh, that's very kind
of you, Bruno.

06:13.634 --> 06:15.113
We appreciate it.

06:15.157 --> 06:16.637
Please thank him
for his generosity.

06:16.680 --> 06:19.596
[speaking Italian]

06:21.381 --> 06:24.296
[speaking Italian]

06:26.298 --> 06:29.258
Bruno would like for you
to come see him tomorrow.

06:29.301 --> 06:30.477
Oh.

06:30.520 --> 06:31.521
[dramatic music]

06:31.565 --> 06:32.914
Capisce?

06:32.957 --> 06:34.742
♪

06:34.785 --> 06:37.266
Okay.Yeah?

06:37.309 --> 06:39.137
[speaking Italian]

06:39.181 --> 06:41.575
Mangia, mangia, mangia.
Eat, eat, eat.

06:41.618 --> 06:43.403
TONY: Grazie. FRANCIS: Grazie mille.

06:45.143 --> 06:46.449
[clears throat]

06:46.493 --> 06:48.451
Uh, Tony.

06:48.495 --> 06:51.759
Is Bruno by any chance, uh...

06:51.802 --> 06:53.761
mafia?

06:53.804 --> 06:56.067
Si, Cosa Nostra.

06:56.111 --> 06:58.592
They run everything here.Okay.

07:00.028 --> 07:01.377
[clears throat]

07:06.208 --> 07:08.689
You okay?

07:08.732 --> 07:10.386
We need to get out of here.

07:10.430 --> 07:13.345
[lively music]

07:13.389 --> 07:14.912
♪

07:14.956 --> 07:16.784
Why are we leaving?

07:16.827 --> 07:19.656
This is like home.Trust me, it's not.

07:19.700 --> 07:21.571
Well, would you please tell me
what happened back there?

07:21.615 --> 07:23.965
Yeah, the mafia happened
back there.

07:24.008 --> 07:26.402
The fucking Cosa Nostra, buddy.
The real fucking thing.

07:26.446 --> 07:27.621
Well, so what?

07:27.664 --> 07:29.274
You dealt with the mafia
back in New York,

07:29.318 --> 07:30.493
and you lived to tell the tale.

07:30.537 --> 07:31.973
Yeah, and I'd like
to keep it that way.

07:32.016 --> 07:33.670
Hey, at least
the food was good, huh?

07:35.455 --> 07:37.631
Wait, there was actually--

07:37.674 --> 07:39.676
there was a town that we saw
on the scout

07:39.720 --> 07:41.809
that would work perfectly.

07:41.852 --> 07:44.507
Uh, Taro--
Taormina? Taormina?

07:44.551 --> 07:46.117
Yes, Taormina.TAVOULARIS: Taormina?

07:46.161 --> 07:47.510
Taormina is beautiful.

07:47.554 --> 07:50.252
Is the Cosa Nostra
in Taormina?

07:50.295 --> 07:51.775
No, not so much there.

07:51.819 --> 07:53.342
Is near the airport.

07:53.385 --> 07:55.387
The airport. Great.

07:55.431 --> 07:57.607
We just flew halfway around
the world to shoot in Burbank.

07:57.651 --> 08:00.480
Wow, Bob's Big Boy.

08:02.482 --> 08:04.092
Yes, I understand that.
We'll have to circle back

08:04.135 --> 08:06.268
around on that because--
I'm sorry.

08:06.311 --> 08:08.705
Mr. Lapidus,
he's not in right now.

08:08.749 --> 08:10.577
And when will you be
expecting him back?

08:10.620 --> 08:12.883
I'm not sure, but I will
have him get right back to you.

08:12.927 --> 08:14.755
[chuckles softly]

08:14.798 --> 08:15.973
Uh--

08:17.279 --> 08:19.673
I'll have to call you
right back.

08:19.716 --> 08:21.544
[door opens]

08:21.588 --> 08:24.329
BART: Sheila,
can you do a deal memo

08:24.373 --> 08:25.809
for Alvin Sargent
to write the adaptation

08:25.853 --> 08:27.507
[door closes]of the book "Addie Pray"?

08:27.550 --> 08:29.291
Um, don't you want to call
Business Affairs?

08:29.334 --> 08:31.075
I want it to come
from this office.

08:31.119 --> 08:33.121
I thought you would've had
enough of authors

08:33.164 --> 08:34.252
writing their own screenplays.

08:34.296 --> 08:36.820
[chuckles]
Barry!

08:36.864 --> 08:38.735
Uh, uh, when did you get in?

08:38.779 --> 08:39.780
Come in.

08:41.695 --> 08:43.261
Right.

08:43.305 --> 08:44.915
Close the door.

08:44.959 --> 08:46.047
Sure.

08:48.223 --> 08:50.530
So, you know, Alvin Sargent

08:50.573 --> 08:51.705
actually didn't write
"Addie Pray."

08:51.748 --> 08:53.968
It was--Where the fuck is Evans?

08:54.011 --> 08:55.883
He's not in.No shit.

08:55.926 --> 08:58.973
Yeah. Um, he's got
a really bad back.

08:59.016 --> 09:00.409
Sciatica.

09:00.452 --> 09:02.846
So, um, he's working
from home.

09:02.890 --> 09:04.413
Ah, I see. Okay.

09:04.456 --> 09:07.503
Well, in that case, he won't
mind if I use his office.

09:07.547 --> 09:09.070
I'm sure that's fine.

09:09.113 --> 09:11.289
Yeah, I'm sure it is, too.

09:11.333 --> 09:13.596
Listen, Peter...
[clears throat]

09:13.640 --> 09:16.468
I want to have a meeting
with you and go over our slate.

09:16.512 --> 09:19.254
Everything in production,
development, everything.

09:19.297 --> 09:21.386
Got it?

09:21.430 --> 09:22.431
Mm-hmm.

09:22.474 --> 09:24.607
Great.Great.

09:27.610 --> 09:30.787
[door opens, closes]

09:30.831 --> 09:33.747
[lively folk music]

09:33.790 --> 09:40.667
♪

10:03.124 --> 10:04.560
Oh.

10:07.084 --> 10:09.652
This is even better
than Corleone.

10:09.696 --> 10:14.657
Uh, yeah, I think I finally
agree with you there, Francis.

10:14.701 --> 10:16.224
TAVOULARIS: Francis, you know,
this could be perfect

10:16.267 --> 10:17.573
for Don Tommasino's estate.

10:17.617 --> 10:19.227
I know.Yeah?

10:19.270 --> 10:21.795
The whole feel
is just spot-on.

10:21.838 --> 10:23.623
Francis, this entire hillside
gets amazing light.

10:23.666 --> 10:24.711
Ooh, you know
what we could do?

10:24.754 --> 10:26.103
This could be
our opening, right?

10:26.147 --> 10:28.018
Do, like, an overhead shot.

10:30.194 --> 10:31.587
Espresso?

10:33.154 --> 10:36.026
[both speaking Italian]

10:38.289 --> 10:40.857
Grazie mille.

10:40.901 --> 10:43.555
[goat bleating][clears throat]

10:43.599 --> 10:46.036
There we go.

10:46.080 --> 10:48.473
BETTYE: This place looks great.RUDDY: Yeah, it's nice.

10:48.517 --> 10:50.040
Very authentic, right?BETTYE: Yeah.

10:50.084 --> 10:52.129
[both chuckle]

10:52.173 --> 10:56.003
[church bell ringing
in distance]

10:56.046 --> 10:57.569
Buongiorno. Buongiorno.

10:57.613 --> 10:59.223
Two coffees, please.

10:59.267 --> 11:01.748
Due espressi, per favore.

11:04.925 --> 11:07.449
You've been
holding back on me.

11:07.492 --> 11:08.885
I've picked up
some phrases.

11:08.929 --> 11:10.539
When in Rome, right?

11:10.582 --> 11:12.715
Yeah, we're not in Rome.Close enough.

11:12.759 --> 11:14.021
[roughly]
Give me your money.

11:14.064 --> 11:17.285
[laughter]

11:17.328 --> 11:18.939
You know what I'm thinking?You're a funny guy.

11:18.982 --> 11:20.767
This would be
a great location

11:20.810 --> 11:23.508
for when Michael meets
Apollonia's father.

11:23.552 --> 11:24.988
Oh, yeah.

11:25.032 --> 11:27.861
Excuse me.
Uh, are you the owner?

11:27.904 --> 11:30.820
[speaking Italian]Okay.

11:30.864 --> 11:33.214
We'd like to have
a conversation with the owner.

11:33.257 --> 11:34.781
Grazie.

11:34.824 --> 11:37.218
What did he just say?

11:37.261 --> 11:39.742
Something in Italian.

11:39.786 --> 11:41.918
So you have
selective Italian?

11:41.962 --> 11:45.835
[both speaking Italian]

11:45.879 --> 11:48.098
I'm Angelo, his son.Angelo.

11:48.142 --> 11:49.143
Al.

11:49.186 --> 11:50.710
This is Francis--

11:53.582 --> 11:55.279
[flirtatious music]

11:55.323 --> 11:57.281
Bettye.

11:57.325 --> 11:59.327
Bettye.

11:59.370 --> 12:00.763
Great.

12:00.807 --> 12:03.418
So, Angelo, we're in town.
We're filming a movie.

12:03.461 --> 12:06.726
We'd love to use
your restaurant as a location.

12:06.769 --> 12:08.640
We'd like to film here.

12:10.686 --> 12:14.037
[both speaking Italian]

12:23.133 --> 12:24.439
50,000 lira.

12:24.482 --> 12:26.267
[scoffs]

12:26.310 --> 12:30.532
♪

12:30.575 --> 12:31.576
Si.

12:31.620 --> 12:32.882
What?

12:32.926 --> 12:35.015
Al, are you sure
we can afford that?

12:35.058 --> 12:36.886
Who's bad
with conversions now, Bettye?

12:36.930 --> 12:38.975
50,000 lira's like 35 bucks.

12:39.019 --> 12:40.498
Come on.
Andiamo.

12:40.542 --> 12:42.196
Can I show you what
we're planning for tomorrow?

12:42.239 --> 12:43.588
Yeah. Grazie.

12:44.981 --> 12:46.766
Grazie.

12:46.809 --> 12:48.071
I'll be back in a little bit.

12:48.115 --> 12:50.595
[chuckles]
Thank you.

12:50.639 --> 12:52.946
Also, I need your help
casting tomorrow.

12:52.989 --> 12:54.121
Casting?Yeah.

12:54.164 --> 12:55.339
What?

12:55.383 --> 12:56.776
Oh!
[speaking Italian]

12:56.819 --> 12:58.908
[camera shutter snaps]

12:58.952 --> 13:00.170
[chuckles]

13:00.214 --> 13:01.302
BETTYE:
Thank you so much.

13:04.871 --> 13:06.350
I ordered a coffee.

13:06.394 --> 13:09.049
Ah, you don't need
so much water.

13:09.092 --> 13:12.530
This is better,
piu Siciliano.

13:15.882 --> 13:18.058
[softly] Ooh, yeah.

13:18.101 --> 13:19.929
Everything is better
in Italy, huh?

13:19.973 --> 13:21.322
[chuckles]

13:21.365 --> 13:24.716
So did you like
any actresses so far?

13:24.760 --> 13:26.980
Well, in the script,

13:27.023 --> 13:30.766
they describe Apollonia
as a thunderbolt.

13:30.810 --> 13:33.813
When Michael sees her,
he immediately falls in love.

13:33.856 --> 13:36.250
You saw a lot
of beautiful girls,

13:36.293 --> 13:37.947
and I'd like to love
all of them.

13:37.991 --> 13:41.037
[chuckles] Yeah.

13:41.081 --> 13:42.909
But it's more than that.

13:42.952 --> 13:45.085
It's about
how she makes you feel.

13:45.128 --> 13:48.740
Not just her beauty,
but the way she looks at you.

13:48.784 --> 13:50.220
PERSON: Scusi.

13:50.264 --> 13:54.137
[speaking Italian]

13:58.968 --> 14:00.709
Sorry, I don't speak
much Italian,

14:00.752 --> 14:03.277
and, uh, you just broke
my translator.

14:03.320 --> 14:05.279
[Angelo clears throat]Do you speak any English?

14:05.322 --> 14:08.499
Yes, I-I think so.

14:08.543 --> 14:11.633
Monday, Tuesday, Wednesday,

14:11.676 --> 14:15.115
Thursday, Friday.[both chuckle]

14:15.158 --> 14:17.682
Come ti chiami?

14:17.726 --> 14:18.945
Simonetta.

14:21.425 --> 14:23.340
FRANCIS:
So--so the dark ones--

14:23.384 --> 14:26.256
GORDY: They've just been
on the tree longer.

14:26.300 --> 14:28.041
They've been there longer
than the younger ones.

14:28.084 --> 14:30.260
More for me?
Thank you so much.

14:30.304 --> 14:31.871
It's really the--hey, no,

14:31.914 --> 14:33.176
you're gonna fill up
on the bread,

14:33.220 --> 14:34.525
and you're gonna ruin
your appetite.

14:34.569 --> 14:35.700
What are you, my mother?

14:35.744 --> 14:37.050
Let's hope
for your mother's sake

14:37.093 --> 14:38.486
she doesn't look
anything like him.

14:38.529 --> 14:39.966
Yeah, right?[all chuckle]

14:40.009 --> 14:41.837
Al, can I steal you
for a second?

14:41.881 --> 14:43.056
Yeah.

14:45.623 --> 14:48.017
GORDY:
You don't want it?

14:48.061 --> 14:49.976
RUDDY: [clears throat]

14:50.019 --> 14:51.194
We have a problem.

14:51.238 --> 14:52.456
Another one?Yeah.

14:52.500 --> 14:55.242
Okay, big or small?

14:55.285 --> 14:56.852
Evans is out.

14:59.028 --> 15:01.204
What? What do you mean?Bluhdorn is going to fire him.

15:03.554 --> 15:04.686
How do you know this?

15:04.729 --> 15:06.340
Because I just got
off the phone

15:06.383 --> 15:07.645
with Bluhdhorn's secretary.

15:10.474 --> 15:12.172
Does Bob know?

15:12.215 --> 15:15.044
It hasn't happened yet,
because no one has seen him.

15:15.088 --> 15:17.090
He hasn't been
in the office in days.

15:17.133 --> 15:19.048
Fuck.

15:20.832 --> 15:22.356
This movie's like a Hydra.

15:22.399 --> 15:25.272
You cut the head off one,
and just another one pops up.

15:25.315 --> 15:27.361
Fuck.

15:27.404 --> 15:30.190
Hey, what do we do?

15:30.233 --> 15:32.061
I mean, I should let him
twist in the wind

15:32.105 --> 15:33.933
for what he said to me.

15:33.976 --> 15:35.543
But you're not going to,

15:35.586 --> 15:37.153
because he is
single-handedly responsible

15:37.197 --> 15:38.285
for giving you your shot.

15:38.328 --> 15:39.590
It's because we need Bob

15:39.634 --> 15:41.679
to finish this movie
the right way.

15:43.681 --> 15:45.553
[sighs] All right,
book us two flights

15:45.596 --> 15:47.207
back to New York tomorrow.

15:47.250 --> 15:48.730
We'll head back
after the car stunt

15:48.773 --> 15:50.688
and let Francis finish
the rest.

15:50.732 --> 15:51.689
Okay.

15:57.521 --> 15:58.783
Yeah, yeah, yeah.

15:58.827 --> 16:00.698
And just the reaction
is just perfect.

16:00.742 --> 16:04.398
Go find some place to be safe,
all right?

16:04.441 --> 16:06.966
Keep an eye out.
How's he doing?

16:07.009 --> 16:09.969
[both speaking Italian]

16:10.012 --> 16:13.015
Gino? Bene?

16:13.059 --> 16:14.974
Si, si. Bene.

16:15.017 --> 16:17.106
Okay, we're ready!Okay.

16:17.150 --> 16:18.803
He understands
we only have the funds

16:18.847 --> 16:19.979
for one shot
of blowing this thing up?

16:20.022 --> 16:22.155
Oh, yes. I made sure.One shot.

16:22.198 --> 16:24.026
Yeah, he know.
I make sure to tell him.

16:24.070 --> 16:27.290
Okay, everybody, please.
Silenzio!

16:27.334 --> 16:28.813
We have one shot to do this,

16:28.857 --> 16:31.164
so everybody
in final positions.

16:31.207 --> 16:34.341
[speaking Italian]

16:36.691 --> 16:39.563
Good luck.
Buona fortuna.

16:39.607 --> 16:40.738
Grazie.

16:42.871 --> 16:43.828
GORDY: We're rolling.

16:45.134 --> 16:48.137
Ready? And set.

16:50.705 --> 16:52.620
Azione!

16:59.627 --> 17:01.585
[bird caws]

17:01.629 --> 17:03.631
FRANCIS:
What happened?

17:03.674 --> 17:06.764
[loud explosion]

17:12.727 --> 17:14.685
[screams]

17:17.775 --> 17:19.908
[shouting in Italian]TAVOULARIS: You get it?

17:19.951 --> 17:22.824
[shouting in Italian]

17:24.608 --> 17:26.523
Is everybody okay?

17:26.567 --> 17:28.395
RUDDY: All right, look.
Okay, listen, I'll handle it.

17:28.438 --> 17:29.744
We didn't mean for that
to happen.

17:29.787 --> 17:32.225
We'll pay for the window.[speaking Italian]

17:32.268 --> 17:35.489
Shit, you know?
Sorry, sorry, scusi.

17:35.532 --> 17:36.664
Al.We'll pay for it.

17:36.707 --> 17:38.144
Yeah?Airport.

17:38.187 --> 17:39.710
Airport. Let's go.

17:39.754 --> 17:41.538
You got it?Okay, all right.

17:41.582 --> 17:42.713
You're eyebrow's on fire.Yeah.

17:42.757 --> 17:44.585
What?

17:44.628 --> 17:47.544
[lively music]

17:47.588 --> 17:48.850
Yeah!

17:50.373 --> 17:51.722
RUDDY:
You can't fire him.

17:51.766 --> 17:53.594
Well, then what am
I supposed to do with him?

17:53.637 --> 17:54.986
He's a lame horse.

17:55.030 --> 17:56.510
And you know what you do
with a lame horse?

17:56.553 --> 17:59.556
Bob Evans is the only reason
that Paramount still exists.

17:59.600 --> 18:00.862
Well, then where is he?

18:00.905 --> 18:02.603
He's supposed to be
running a studio.

18:02.646 --> 18:04.561
I know you Hollywood idiots
think that

18:04.605 --> 18:06.172
it's all make-believe,
but it's still a business.

18:06.215 --> 18:08.478
Nobody understands this
business better than he does.

18:08.522 --> 18:10.567
And it doesn't matter
if he's missing in action.

18:10.611 --> 18:12.482
A business does not run itself.

18:12.526 --> 18:15.703
Charlie, show some
fucking decency, would you?

18:15.746 --> 18:17.574
The guy's given his blood
for your company.

18:17.618 --> 18:19.228
I gave my blood for him!

18:21.012 --> 18:22.666
God damn it!

18:22.710 --> 18:24.625
Everyone told me that
he didn't have what it takes.

18:24.668 --> 18:26.322
Everyone!

18:26.366 --> 18:28.759
But I saw something in him,
and I believed in him,

18:28.803 --> 18:31.110
and I chose to bet on him.

18:32.850 --> 18:34.069
It was a good bet.

18:37.377 --> 18:41.120
He's meshugana,
and he's just crazy enough

18:41.163 --> 18:43.644
to make you believe
his line of bullshit.

18:45.863 --> 18:49.389
He's got that thing,
you know?

18:49.432 --> 18:52.305
It just--it draws you in.

18:52.348 --> 18:54.045
Charisma.

18:55.395 --> 18:57.658
But it's gone now, Ruddy...

18:57.701 --> 19:00.139
that spark.

19:00.182 --> 19:03.881
And I have responsibilities.

19:03.925 --> 19:07.668
I cannot have a drug addict
running my company.

19:10.410 --> 19:13.456
Lapidus is in LA
to look out for things.

19:13.500 --> 19:15.284
He's in charge for now.

19:21.247 --> 19:24.119
Let me talk to Bob.

19:24.163 --> 19:26.687
Without him,
this movie won't succeed.

19:26.730 --> 19:28.645
And after everything
he's done for the company,

19:28.689 --> 19:32.127
at the very least,
that deserves a meeting.

19:32.171 --> 19:34.129
But that window
is closing fast.

19:34.173 --> 19:37.088
[gentle piano music]

19:37.132 --> 19:39.221
♪

19:39.265 --> 19:41.876
I'm gonna talk to him.

19:41.919 --> 19:48.883
♪

19:48.926 --> 19:50.885
[distant bell ringing]

19:50.928 --> 19:53.148
All right, should we start
with the development slate?

19:53.192 --> 19:55.890
Yeah.Yeah?

19:55.933 --> 19:57.718
Okay.

19:57.761 --> 20:00.895
So, as you can see,

20:00.938 --> 20:02.940
we got quite a list here--"Great Gatsby."

20:02.984 --> 20:04.159
Yeah.I love that book.

20:04.203 --> 20:06.901
Reminded me of my father.

20:06.944 --> 20:10.339
Uh, what is this?
Uh, the "Save the Tiger"?

20:10.383 --> 20:11.862
What tiger? What is this?Yeah.

20:11.906 --> 20:14.474
That's based on a novel
by Steve Shagan.

20:14.517 --> 20:15.866
We optioned the galleys.

20:15.910 --> 20:16.867
It hasn't been published yet,

20:16.911 --> 20:18.391
but it's
a great character study.

20:18.434 --> 20:20.610
This--this man
with an apparel company

20:20.654 --> 20:22.133
who can't keep it afloat,

20:22.177 --> 20:24.005
and he's going down
a dark rabbit hole.

20:24.048 --> 20:25.659
Stop right there.

20:25.702 --> 20:27.878
Who the hell wants to see that?
[chuckles]

20:27.922 --> 20:31.099
Barry, this is
a prestige project.

20:31.142 --> 20:33.667
I guess Evans misses
lady's apparel after all.

20:33.710 --> 20:35.495
You do know that we are

20:35.538 --> 20:38.454
in the entertainment
business, right?

20:38.498 --> 20:40.239
There's more to it than that.

20:40.282 --> 20:42.371
Oh, and this,
no, no, no, no, no.

20:42.415 --> 20:44.243
"Chinatown," no.

20:44.286 --> 20:45.461
What?

20:47.898 --> 20:49.552
I'm--I'm sorry.

20:49.596 --> 20:51.728
That's a--
that's a really great script.

20:51.772 --> 20:53.991
Um, inspired by real events.

20:54.035 --> 20:57.386
Yeah, water, I get it.
I heard Evans' pitch, right?

20:57.430 --> 20:58.953
Dump it.

20:58.996 --> 21:00.084
Dump it?

21:00.128 --> 21:01.347
Sell it.

21:01.390 --> 21:03.305
Or we'll have to take
a loss on it.

21:03.349 --> 21:07.178
We should be making what
the people want to see, right?

21:07.222 --> 21:10.007
"Airport,"
a thriller in the sky.

21:10.051 --> 21:11.618
"M.A.S.H.," funny doctors.

21:11.661 --> 21:13.402
Again, entertainment.

21:15.361 --> 21:18.407
I'm sorry, Barry, um...
[chuckles weakly]

21:18.451 --> 21:21.323
"Chinatown" can really be
something.

21:21.367 --> 21:23.412
You know, uh, uh,
Nicholson's attached.

21:23.456 --> 21:25.501
It does not matter
who is in it

21:25.545 --> 21:29.897
if it's another dark,
confusing piece, but go ahead,

21:29.940 --> 21:31.333
give me the elevator pitch.

21:31.377 --> 21:33.857
Okay.
It's about original sin.

21:33.901 --> 21:35.294
It's about the sin
of stolen water

21:35.337 --> 21:37.339
and the sin of incest

21:37.383 --> 21:40.516
and how politics and greed
connects them.

21:41.822 --> 21:43.563
But it's more than
just a pitch.

21:43.606 --> 21:47.131
It's the actor, the director,
the big picture.

21:47.175 --> 21:50.961
That movie is really
coming together.

21:51.005 --> 21:52.746
No.[pen clicks]

21:52.789 --> 21:55.662
I'm not green-lighting anything
I don't understand, all right?

21:55.705 --> 21:58.882
We're gonna stop developing
these rarified flights of fancy

21:58.926 --> 22:00.884
and start applying
some good business sense

22:00.928 --> 22:02.408
to what we do here.

22:05.149 --> 22:09.632
[doorbell ringing]

22:26.562 --> 22:27.650
Bob, open up.

22:29.957 --> 22:31.654
[knocking on door]

22:31.698 --> 22:33.917
Come on, Bob, open up.
It's me. It's Al.

22:33.961 --> 22:36.920
[melancholy piano music]

22:36.964 --> 22:39.445
[knocking continues]

22:39.488 --> 22:41.708
Bob, open up, buddy.

22:41.751 --> 22:45.625
♪

22:47.366 --> 22:50.107
Hey, it's Caesar.

22:50.151 --> 22:51.500
Okay.

22:55.286 --> 22:57.071
BETTYE: Caesar,
I have Al coming to you

22:57.114 --> 23:00.379
in three, two...

23:00.422 --> 23:02.119
[phone beeps]Caesar.

23:02.163 --> 23:03.773
CAESAR:
How they hanging?

23:03.817 --> 23:06.297
Low and ready for trouble.

23:06.341 --> 23:07.777
Hey, how's Joe doing?

23:07.821 --> 23:09.779
Same.

23:09.823 --> 23:11.694
How's the movie going?

23:11.738 --> 23:13.304
Good. We're getting close.

23:13.348 --> 23:14.741
That's great.

23:14.784 --> 23:15.829
You know, we're all really
looking forward

23:15.872 --> 23:17.004
to the premiere.

23:17.047 --> 23:18.701
You have a date yet?

23:18.745 --> 23:22.662
Boss wanted to invite
some of our...associates.

23:22.705 --> 23:25.055
Yeah, listen, about that...

23:25.099 --> 23:26.622
I know I said
I would donate the proceeds

23:26.666 --> 23:27.971
to an Italian League charity,

23:28.015 --> 23:29.451
but Gulf and Western's
not gonna let me do that.

23:29.495 --> 23:31.018
Eh, forget about it.

23:31.061 --> 23:33.324
Boss was never gonna
hold you to that.

23:33.368 --> 23:34.978
Okay, great.

23:35.022 --> 23:37.328
I just didn't want you guys
thinking that I forgot.

23:37.372 --> 23:39.069
We wouldn't have
thought that.

23:41.245 --> 23:44.118
Is there anything we can do
to help Joe?

23:44.161 --> 23:46.860
You got a direct line
to God?

23:46.903 --> 23:48.601
[sighs]
Look, I got to go.

23:48.644 --> 23:51.430
But, um, let me know
about that premiere, all right?

23:51.473 --> 23:53.432
I want to get a new suit.

23:54.520 --> 23:55.825
[line clicks,
dial tone buzzes]

23:55.869 --> 23:57.740
Hey.

23:57.784 --> 23:59.263
You know you can't invite
those guys

23:59.307 --> 24:00.395
to the premiere, right?

24:00.439 --> 24:01.875
Charlie would murder you.

24:01.918 --> 24:04.660
I know, but I gave my word.

24:04.704 --> 24:07.924
So what are you gonna do?

24:07.968 --> 24:10.753
[phone ringing]Oh.

24:13.234 --> 24:15.454
Al Ruddy's office.

24:15.497 --> 24:18.587
Yes, sir, I'll tell him.

24:18.631 --> 24:20.850
Lapidus wants to see you.

24:20.894 --> 24:23.070
Great. Where?

24:23.113 --> 24:25.202
In Evans' office.

24:25.246 --> 24:26.552
Fuck.

24:28.641 --> 24:31.252
[sighs]

24:31.295 --> 24:34.342
[upbeat music]

24:34.385 --> 24:36.387
Try Evans again.
Let it ring until he picks up.

24:36.431 --> 24:38.433
♪

24:40.783 --> 24:43.133
[knocking on door,
door opens]

24:43.177 --> 24:45.135
Oh.

24:45.179 --> 24:47.616
How was Italy?

24:47.660 --> 24:50.184
Fine.

24:50.227 --> 24:53.187
Why did you stop
in New York on the way back?

24:53.230 --> 24:54.449
Ooh...

24:54.493 --> 24:56.495
I wanted a good bagel.
Ah.

24:56.538 --> 24:58.584
Just isn't the same
out here in LA.

25:01.064 --> 25:03.632
I'm working on "The Godfather"
while Evans is out.

25:03.676 --> 25:08.071
Apparently he's got
a bad back, poor fella.

25:08.115 --> 25:11.248
Well, I think we can manage
until he's back on his feet.

25:11.292 --> 25:14.208
Oh, we don't know when
or even if that'll happen.

25:14.251 --> 25:15.557
It'll happen.

25:15.601 --> 25:18.125
When will I see a cut
of "The Godfather"?

25:18.168 --> 25:20.997
Francis is still shooting.

25:21.041 --> 25:22.912
Yes, I know.

25:22.956 --> 25:25.654
He's in Sicily wasting money.

25:25.698 --> 25:27.003
It was always
in the budget.

25:27.047 --> 25:29.702
I want to see that cut
as soon as possible.

25:31.442 --> 25:33.183
He'll be back
end of the week,

25:33.227 --> 25:34.837
and our editor's standing by.

25:34.881 --> 25:37.361
Great.

25:37.405 --> 25:38.711
Great.[phone beeps]

25:38.754 --> 25:42.062
SHEILA: I've got Bluhdorn
on line one.

25:42.105 --> 25:44.151
Thank you, Sheila.

25:44.194 --> 25:47.110
[upbeat bass music]

25:47.154 --> 25:52.463
♪

25:52.507 --> 25:53.464
Charlie.

26:01.124 --> 26:02.778
[reel slows, stops]

26:02.822 --> 26:05.781
[focused music]

26:05.825 --> 26:12.353
♪

26:17.663 --> 26:19.360
That one there.

26:19.403 --> 26:26.323
♪

26:44.690 --> 26:46.430
How's it looking?

26:49.303 --> 26:51.087
You want to see
for yourself?

26:53.133 --> 26:56.005
[sweeping dramatic music
playing]

26:56.049 --> 27:02.969
♪

27:05.754 --> 27:07.669
[lights click]

27:14.154 --> 27:16.547
[sighs]

27:16.591 --> 27:18.767
Well, I guess
no reaction is a reaction.

27:21.509 --> 27:22.989
We got it.

27:23.032 --> 27:24.164
What?

27:24.207 --> 27:25.644
Come here.Oh.

27:25.687 --> 27:28.429
Oh, it's--it's beautiful.
It's beautiful.

27:28.472 --> 27:30.561
It's better than I ever
thought it could be.

27:30.605 --> 27:32.085
Buddy, it's so good.

27:32.128 --> 27:33.782
[crying]
Jesus, fuck. Thank you.

27:33.826 --> 27:36.306
It is so powerful.
It...

27:36.350 --> 27:38.308
FRANCIS: Yeah.And Sicily.

27:38.352 --> 27:40.136
My God, it looks so beautiful.

27:40.180 --> 27:41.572
It was worth us fighting
to go there.

27:41.616 --> 27:42.617
RUDDY:
Yes, yes.

27:42.661 --> 27:43.792
I know.Yep, absolutely.

27:43.836 --> 27:45.489
Absolutely.

27:45.533 --> 27:47.927
I want to show it
to Evans.

27:47.970 --> 27:49.232
Yeah,
I think it's ready.

27:49.276 --> 27:50.756
I think it's ready.Okay.

27:50.799 --> 27:52.279
Well, get him in here.
I want to show him right now.

27:52.322 --> 27:53.584
Put it on the screen
right now.

27:53.628 --> 27:55.282
RUDDY: I'm gonna--
I got to talk to him.

27:55.325 --> 27:57.676
He's dealing with some
back issues right now, but--

27:57.719 --> 27:59.242
but he's--he's excited.Yeah.

27:59.286 --> 28:00.896
It's ready for him.

28:00.940 --> 28:02.942
[exhales heavily]
Okay.

28:02.985 --> 28:06.336
[all chuckle]Um, I'm going to...

28:06.380 --> 28:08.077
get some sleep, then.

28:08.121 --> 28:09.426
A shower couldn't hurt.

28:09.470 --> 28:11.559
[chuckles weakly]

28:11.602 --> 28:14.040
You know what Evans
told me?

28:14.083 --> 28:16.520
He said the movie
makes 50 mil,

28:16.564 --> 28:17.957
he's gonna buy me
whatever car I want.

28:18.000 --> 28:19.436
[laughs]It's good to be you.

28:22.744 --> 28:23.745
[door opens]

28:23.789 --> 28:25.573
How are we gonna
show it to Evans

28:25.616 --> 28:28.054
when he isn't answering
your calls?

28:28.097 --> 28:30.447
I don't know.

28:30.491 --> 28:33.015
Also, Caesar called
about the premiere.

28:33.059 --> 28:35.278
They're really expecting
to go.

28:37.803 --> 28:39.108
Good news--

28:39.152 --> 28:40.893
Bogdanovich wants to direct

28:40.936 --> 28:42.503
after he's finished with post
on "What's up, Doc?"

28:42.546 --> 28:45.245
Great.He also--

28:45.288 --> 28:48.727
he wants to change the name
to "Paper Moon."

28:48.770 --> 28:50.337
Well, I'm not sure
how that applies,

28:50.380 --> 28:51.817
but it's a great title.

28:51.860 --> 28:53.819
Now, I see you've done
your homework.

28:53.862 --> 28:55.646
Uh, what's your take
on adapting this?

28:55.690 --> 28:57.213
[knocking on door]Well--

28:57.257 --> 28:58.519
Peter.

28:58.562 --> 29:01.827
Hey.
Uh, I'm in a creative meeting.

29:01.870 --> 29:04.003
Barry Lapidus.Alvin Sargent.

29:04.046 --> 29:06.570
Eh, Barry,
did you need something?

29:06.614 --> 29:08.921
No.
It can wait.

29:08.964 --> 29:11.358
I think I'll, uh, sit in.
Please, continue.

29:11.401 --> 29:12.968
[clears throat]

29:14.927 --> 29:17.756
Uh, so--

29:17.799 --> 29:22.021
Well, I love the relationship
between Moses and Addie.

29:22.064 --> 29:24.153
Uh, I've never seen anything
like that.

29:24.197 --> 29:27.635
Sometime partner in crime,
sometimes father/daughter.

29:27.678 --> 29:29.680
But she'd never admit
that she wants a father figure.

29:29.724 --> 29:31.857
Well, girls need
their fathers.

29:33.902 --> 29:36.470
It's important that we never
play him talking down to her

29:36.513 --> 29:39.212
as if she's
a regular nine-year-old.

29:39.255 --> 29:40.866
She was older
in the book, right?

29:40.909 --> 29:43.129
Yeah, I'd age her down
a few years.

29:43.172 --> 29:45.653
Make it even more shocking
that this little kid

29:45.696 --> 29:46.872
is so good at being
a con artist.

29:46.915 --> 29:48.438
BARRY:
Well, my daughter is 12,

29:48.482 --> 29:50.701
and I think she'd relate
to a 12-year-old

29:50.745 --> 29:52.965
more than a 9-year-old.

29:53.008 --> 29:54.836
Let's make her 12.

29:54.880 --> 29:56.882
You need to keep
the audience in mind.

29:56.925 --> 30:01.538
Do they really want to see
a young kid as a con artist?

30:01.582 --> 30:05.412
[sighs] That's what's so unique
about the book.

30:05.455 --> 30:06.805
Have you read it?

30:06.848 --> 30:09.068
Skimmed.

30:09.111 --> 30:11.679
[exhales softly] It's not
about her being a criminal.

30:11.722 --> 30:13.333
It's about her secret longing

30:13.376 --> 30:15.857
for the family
that she's never had.

30:15.901 --> 30:18.555
And she is the key
to redemption

30:18.599 --> 30:19.818
for the Moses character.

30:19.861 --> 30:21.863
Yeah.
He's--he's more the child

30:21.907 --> 30:24.257
because he caves in
to her every whim,

30:24.300 --> 30:26.041
her every desire.

30:26.085 --> 30:27.869
He can't see past
his own ambition.

30:32.961 --> 30:34.789
Well...
[clears throat]

30:34.833 --> 30:36.791
I'm sorry to have to leave,
but I've got a thing.

30:36.835 --> 30:38.140
It was nice to meet you.

30:38.184 --> 30:40.490
Peter, I'll catch up
with you later.

30:42.884 --> 30:44.190
[door opens]

30:46.235 --> 30:47.846
Jesus!

30:51.066 --> 30:53.025
FELIX: Oh, man.

30:53.068 --> 30:57.246
Why can't I do
just one lousy thing right?

30:59.292 --> 31:02.904
[loud crash] Ow! I hurt my arm.

31:02.948 --> 31:05.428
You're hopeless.
You're a hopeless mental case.

31:05.472 --> 31:06.908
[chuckles]

31:06.952 --> 31:09.693
FELIX: I can't throw
with that arm--I got bursitis.

31:09.737 --> 31:11.739
I hope you don't mind
I let myself in.

31:11.782 --> 31:13.306
OSCAR: Leave your meals
outside the doors.

31:13.349 --> 31:15.221
The window was open. Slide in the newspapers.

31:15.264 --> 31:16.787
FELIX: Oh, shut it, Oscar.
I hurt easily.

31:16.831 --> 31:18.528
And that's the way I am,
and I can't help it.

31:18.572 --> 31:19.921
Well, you're not gonna cry,
are you?

31:19.965 --> 31:22.010
I think all those tears
dripping on your arm

31:22.054 --> 31:25.318
is what gave you bursitis.

31:25.361 --> 31:27.668
What's going on here, Bob?

31:27.711 --> 31:28.930
Watching a movie.

31:28.974 --> 31:31.933
No. I mean,
what's going on with you?

31:31.977 --> 31:33.195
I've called you 50 times.

31:33.239 --> 31:34.893
Nobody's seen you
in God knows how long.

31:34.936 --> 31:36.546
[chuckles]

31:36.590 --> 31:39.332
He's a fucking genius.

31:39.375 --> 31:40.942
OSCAR:
How?

31:40.986 --> 31:43.553
[projector clicks]

31:43.597 --> 31:45.599
People are worried
about you.

31:45.642 --> 31:48.297
[sighs]
Who cares, Al?

31:48.341 --> 31:50.517
You?Yeah, me.

31:50.560 --> 31:53.085
Francis, Charlie.Bluhdorn?

31:53.128 --> 31:57.089
He's probably got Barry
redecorating my office by now.

31:57.132 --> 31:59.047
None of it matters.Yes, it does.

31:59.091 --> 32:00.744
It doesn't.Yes, it does.

32:00.788 --> 32:03.312
But you can't just disappear
on us now, Bob.

32:03.356 --> 32:04.444
We need you.

32:04.487 --> 32:07.012
I'm a bad guru.

32:07.055 --> 32:08.796
I'm a false idol.

32:10.798 --> 32:12.408
What happened with Ali?

32:14.497 --> 32:17.152
She's gone...

32:17.196 --> 32:18.762
and I can't get her back.

32:18.806 --> 32:20.547
Yes, you can.

32:20.590 --> 32:22.331
It's never too late, but you
got to get your shit together.

32:22.375 --> 32:24.333
Interesting.

32:24.377 --> 32:25.682
Yeah, I never thought of that.

32:25.726 --> 32:28.555
Get my shit together.
Huh, piece of cake.

32:28.598 --> 32:32.994
Well, that won't take back
my wife fucking Steve McQueen.

32:38.608 --> 32:39.783
I'm sorry to hear that.

32:39.827 --> 32:41.611
Oh, go away, Al.

32:41.655 --> 32:43.744
Just let me fucking rot
in peace would you?

32:43.787 --> 32:45.920
Please, please.

32:45.964 --> 32:48.096
Look...
[clears throat]

32:50.316 --> 32:54.189
I'm no expert
on any of this either.

32:54.233 --> 32:57.584
I fucked up my relationship
with Francoise...

32:57.627 --> 32:59.107
and I really loved her.

32:59.151 --> 33:01.240
It hurt like hell
when she left me.

33:01.283 --> 33:04.025
[clears throat]

33:04.069 --> 33:05.418
And all she really wanted

33:05.461 --> 33:07.463
was a piece of me
that I couldn't give her

33:07.507 --> 33:09.944
because I was giving it all
to this movie.

33:12.468 --> 33:14.993
Bob, I'm here
because I care about you,

33:15.036 --> 33:16.516
but also because
"The Godfather"

33:16.559 --> 33:18.300
needs its godfather.

33:18.344 --> 33:19.780
You can't ignore
who you really are.

33:19.823 --> 33:21.521
Oh, God.
I mean, who am I?

33:21.564 --> 33:23.044
You're a fucking maverick.

33:23.088 --> 33:24.263
You're the guy that told me,

33:24.306 --> 33:25.786
"Do whatever it takes
to get it done."

33:25.829 --> 33:28.310
I'm no maverick.
What the fuck?

33:30.399 --> 33:32.880
I'm an illusion...

33:32.923 --> 33:35.361
a character.

33:35.404 --> 33:39.147
Looks great on screen,
but it's just pretend.

33:39.191 --> 33:40.409
That's not true.

33:40.453 --> 33:41.584
What--what are you
talking about?

33:41.628 --> 33:44.065
We--we're all pretending.
Look at you.

33:44.109 --> 33:46.067
Pencil pusher...

33:46.111 --> 33:48.417
who thinks
he's a producer.

33:48.461 --> 33:51.551
Look at me. Fuck.

33:51.594 --> 33:55.033
Shitty actor
becomes the king of Hollywood.

33:55.076 --> 33:57.470
I mean, if that--
if that's not pretending,

33:57.513 --> 34:00.168
I--[chuckling]
I don't what the fuck is.

34:00.212 --> 34:02.562
[scoffs]

34:02.605 --> 34:05.304
Yeah.

34:05.347 --> 34:08.263
[soft solemn music]

34:08.307 --> 34:11.440
♪

34:11.484 --> 34:14.661
I just wanted it so bad...

34:14.704 --> 34:19.318
prove to the world
there's only one Bob Evans.

34:19.361 --> 34:21.407
I could do it
on my own terms.

34:21.450 --> 34:24.105
[exhales deeply]

34:24.149 --> 34:28.109
Power, prestige...

34:28.153 --> 34:30.372
perfect girl on my arm.

34:33.114 --> 34:36.248
I fell in love with it all.

34:36.291 --> 34:38.119
Particularly the girl,
you know?

34:38.163 --> 34:39.555
[sighs]

34:39.599 --> 34:43.429
I can't--I can't--
[breath catching]

34:43.472 --> 34:46.258
I can't fucking do it
without her, all right?

34:46.301 --> 34:48.738
♪

34:48.782 --> 34:51.393
Nope. No.

34:53.830 --> 34:56.268
Bob, think about
all the films that you've done.

34:56.311 --> 34:58.226
That's who you are,
with or without her.

34:58.270 --> 35:00.881
None of it's fucking real!
None of it!

35:00.924 --> 35:02.883
Oh, yes, it is, or at least
it fucking better be,

35:02.926 --> 35:04.667
because we've sacrificed
too much

35:04.711 --> 35:06.495
for it not to mean anything.

35:06.539 --> 35:08.280
And as much
as I'd like to think

35:08.323 --> 35:10.412
that if either one of us had
the opportunity to go back

35:10.456 --> 35:12.153
that we do anything
fucking different,

35:12.197 --> 35:14.155
I know that we wouldn't.

35:14.199 --> 35:16.984
♪

35:17.027 --> 35:18.986
With guys like us...

35:19.029 --> 35:20.814
♪

35:20.857 --> 35:22.598
There comes a point
where there is no separation

35:22.642 --> 35:25.688
between who we are
and what we do.

35:25.732 --> 35:28.822
And this...

35:28.865 --> 35:30.650
this is who we are.

35:34.219 --> 35:37.918
Al...[sighs]

35:37.961 --> 35:40.573
I-I don't know.

35:40.616 --> 35:42.705
I-I don't know
if it's worth it anymore, man.

35:42.749 --> 35:45.317
I really don't, you know?

35:45.360 --> 35:49.364
♪

35:49.408 --> 35:50.670
It has to be.

35:50.713 --> 35:57.633
♪

36:00.070 --> 36:04.292
[projector clicks] OSCAR: Beginning to listen.

36:04.336 --> 36:06.164
FELIX: You're not gonna hear
another peep out of me.

36:06.207 --> 36:07.774
OSCAR: You're not gonna
give me a haircut, are you?

36:07.817 --> 36:09.515
FELIX: I'm gonna cut up
some cabbage and greens

36:09.558 --> 36:11.212
and make coleslaw
for tomorrow.

36:11.256 --> 36:12.866
OSCAR: I don't want
any coleslaw for tomorrow.

36:12.909 --> 36:14.172
I just want to have
some fun tonight.

36:14.215 --> 36:15.695
FELIX: Thought you liked
my coleslaw.

36:15.738 --> 36:17.262
OSCAR: I love your coleslaw. FELIX: Uh-huh.

36:17.305 --> 36:18.915
OSCAR: I swear, Felix,
I love your coleslaw.

36:18.959 --> 36:21.179
I'll take your coleslaw
with me to work tomorrow

36:21.222 --> 36:22.919
but not tonight--
let's go out of the house.

36:22.963 --> 36:24.704
All right, let's go.

36:24.747 --> 36:26.271
I only make it for you.
I don't like coleslaw.

36:26.314 --> 36:27.663
If you wanted to get out
of the house,

36:27.707 --> 36:28.751
why didn't you say so
in the first place?

36:32.842 --> 36:35.236
BARRY:
"Murder. Mayhem. Mafia."

36:36.672 --> 36:38.892
That's sharp.
That's really sharp.

36:38.935 --> 36:40.372
"Murder. Mayhem. Mafia."
I like that.

36:40.415 --> 36:42.374
No, no.
We can't have the word "mafia"

36:42.417 --> 36:44.637
on the poster.

36:44.680 --> 36:46.160
What else are you guys
thinking?

36:57.563 --> 37:00.392
Hmm.
I'm not sure about the cat.

37:00.435 --> 37:02.394
Really?
The cat's the problem?

37:02.437 --> 37:03.786
I just don't get it.

37:03.830 --> 37:05.788
What is this saying
about our film?

37:05.832 --> 37:08.922
He's powerful, dangerous,
and has a soft side.

37:08.965 --> 37:11.316
[chuckling]
Oh, I see.

37:11.359 --> 37:13.796
The cat represents
the soft side,

37:13.840 --> 37:15.668
and the tagline,
"Take the Cannoli,"

37:15.711 --> 37:17.322
that's because he has
a sweet tooth, right?

37:17.365 --> 37:19.149
BART:
These are just preliminary.

37:19.193 --> 37:20.716
That's--that's the point
of this meeting.

37:20.760 --> 37:22.849
So that the marketing team can
hear from the creatives, too.

37:22.892 --> 37:25.286
Well, I think the approach
is just a little off, okay?

37:25.330 --> 37:26.853
Our film is about power.

37:26.896 --> 37:30.160
Who holds the strings
and manipulates everything?

37:30.204 --> 37:31.945
That is why I think
we should use

37:31.988 --> 37:33.599
the cover of the book
as the poster.

37:33.642 --> 37:35.383
Agreed.

37:35.427 --> 37:37.777
No, one's gonna know
what that is, right?

37:37.820 --> 37:41.346
People are gonna think it's
a Nazi movie or something.

37:41.389 --> 37:43.957
Nazi?What the fuck?

37:44.000 --> 37:46.264
That's not
a fucking swastika, Barry.

37:46.307 --> 37:47.830
Those are marionette strings.

37:47.874 --> 37:50.180
I know that, Ruddy.

37:50.224 --> 37:52.400
Look, these guys have worked on
hundreds of movies, all right?

37:52.444 --> 37:54.010
They know what they're doing.

37:54.054 --> 37:55.403
So you make the movie,

37:55.447 --> 37:58.493
and let the adults
figure out the poster, okay?

38:00.539 --> 38:03.106
Top-notch work, guys.
Thank you.

38:03.150 --> 38:04.978
Where the hell is Evans?

38:05.021 --> 38:08.721
Barry, why don't
we hear the guys out?

38:08.764 --> 38:11.158
You know, the cover is from the
bestselling book of the year.

38:11.201 --> 38:12.942
[door closes]

38:12.986 --> 38:14.161
You want me
to hear these guys out?

38:14.204 --> 38:15.380
Why?

38:15.423 --> 38:17.251
Because they're so good
at delivering?

38:17.295 --> 38:18.600
That's an interesting thought,

38:18.644 --> 38:19.993
because the only thing
that they've delivered

38:20.036 --> 38:22.125
is a movie
that's 45 minutes too long.

38:22.169 --> 38:23.605
Yeah, well, Evans
hasn't given his notes yet.

38:23.649 --> 38:24.954
So what?

38:24.998 --> 38:26.173
You shouldn't
have seen it yet.

38:26.216 --> 38:29.176
Well, I have seen it,
and I can't unsee it.

38:29.219 --> 38:31.004
So welcome
to Hollywood, Francis.

38:31.047 --> 38:34.181
I didn't realize
you were new to this.

38:36.009 --> 38:39.099
This movie cannot be longer
than two hours.

38:39.142 --> 38:41.580
[shouts]
Did you even like it?

38:41.623 --> 38:43.408
It was a little slow
for my taste.

38:43.451 --> 38:44.670
I mean,
that whole Sicily thing?

38:44.713 --> 38:46.367
Why?It's Michael's tipping point.

38:46.411 --> 38:49.239
He understands that his life
can no longer be uncomplicated.

38:49.283 --> 38:50.719
Well, it's a waste.
Cut it.

38:50.763 --> 38:53.505
No, it's important
for the storytelling.

38:53.548 --> 38:55.507
You want to know what's
important for the storytelling?

38:55.550 --> 38:57.900
Maximum plays per screen.

38:57.944 --> 39:01.251
A normal two-hour movie can run
five showings in a day,

39:01.295 --> 39:04.777
but your masterpiece
can only run three or four

39:04.820 --> 39:06.605
because it's too long.

39:06.648 --> 39:09.912
Now, that is 20% less
box office.

39:09.956 --> 39:11.349
And money, gentlemen,

39:11.392 --> 39:13.263
whether you care
to admit it or not,

39:13.307 --> 39:14.830
it's important,

39:14.874 --> 39:16.789
'cause otherwise,
movies don't get made.

39:16.832 --> 39:19.705
Well, it doesn't matter
if the movie's not any good

39:19.748 --> 39:21.489
because nobody's gonna be
in the fucking theater

39:21.533 --> 39:23.709
for the maximum plays per day.

39:23.752 --> 39:24.927
All right--RUDDY: Who gives a shit?

39:24.971 --> 39:26.886
Is there a compromise
to be had here?

39:26.929 --> 39:29.410
Yes, there is.
Cut 30 minutes.

39:29.454 --> 39:30.933
It's not an option.

39:30.977 --> 39:34.894
[dramatic music]

39:34.937 --> 39:37.810
Better get cracking, gentlemen,
or I'll cut it myself.

39:37.853 --> 39:42.771
♪

39:42.815 --> 39:44.120
Ruddy--

39:46.122 --> 39:52.999
♪

39:57.525 --> 39:59.353
What do you think?

39:59.397 --> 40:01.616
That work?

40:01.660 --> 40:04.010
I don't know.

40:04.053 --> 40:06.752
♪

40:06.795 --> 40:10.799
[breathes deeply]

40:10.843 --> 40:15.021
You want me to run it again?

40:15.064 --> 40:17.850
Do whatever you want.
They're ruining my picture.

40:17.893 --> 40:21.723
♪

40:25.031 --> 40:27.207
[knocking on door]Come in.

40:30.210 --> 40:31.516
Hi.

40:37.043 --> 40:41.047
You were, uh, a little rough
on them in that meeting.

40:41.090 --> 40:42.483
They're big boys, Peter.

40:42.527 --> 40:45.268
I don't have to pander
to spoiled children.

40:45.312 --> 40:46.661
Actually, you do, Barry.

40:50.056 --> 40:54.800
Look, if you're stepping
into Evans' shoes...

40:54.843 --> 40:58.281
you need to understand
what he actually does...

40:58.325 --> 41:00.196
and what he's really good at.

41:00.240 --> 41:02.764
I've got my own shoes.
I don't need Bob's.

41:02.808 --> 41:04.723
The creatives
aren't just monkeys

41:04.766 --> 41:06.420
with pens and typewriters.

41:06.464 --> 41:08.814
They--they have a real vision
for the film.

41:08.857 --> 41:09.858
I mean, they know it better
than anybody.

41:09.902 --> 41:11.817
Yeah, and I know what sells.

41:11.860 --> 41:14.515
Yes, you do,
and that is great,

41:14.559 --> 41:16.474
but it's more than that.

41:16.517 --> 41:18.998
It's--it's using the creatives

41:19.041 --> 41:21.217
to guide the marketing
so we can come up

41:21.261 --> 41:23.568
with something unique
and eye-catching.

41:23.611 --> 41:26.353
It's nurturing their talent
to write the best script,

41:26.396 --> 41:28.486
to direct the best film.

41:28.529 --> 41:30.139
And it's talking over character
and themes--

41:30.183 --> 41:33.012
Bob isn't here, Peter, okay?

41:35.275 --> 41:39.409
So his shoes, no matter
how big and creative they are,

41:39.453 --> 41:43.588
they will remain empty,
in a closet, forgotten.

41:43.631 --> 41:44.937
Okay?

41:46.591 --> 41:50.029
[sighs quietly]

41:50.072 --> 41:51.726
Okay.

41:51.770 --> 41:55.513
[melancholy piano music]

41:55.556 --> 41:57.384
Okay.

41:57.427 --> 42:04.347
♪

42:05.697 --> 42:09.265
You're a valuable asset, Peter.

42:09.309 --> 42:10.832
You are.

42:12.486 --> 42:14.575
So I, uh...

42:14.619 --> 42:17.273
I hope that
you'll remain on board.

42:17.317 --> 42:20.146
♪

42:20.189 --> 42:22.496
I wasn't criticizing you,
Barry.

42:22.540 --> 42:24.237
I was trying to help you.

42:24.280 --> 42:30.765
♪

42:30.809 --> 42:33.333
[door closes][sighs]

42:33.376 --> 42:37.293
♪

42:37.337 --> 42:39.513
[sighs]

42:39.557 --> 42:46.476
♪

43:34.133 --> 43:35.656
Good night, Sheila.

43:35.700 --> 43:38.354
Good night, Mr. Evans--

43:38.398 --> 43:39.573
Mr. Lapidus.

43:42.794 --> 43:44.143
Good night.

43:44.186 --> 43:49.975
♪

43:50.018 --> 43:51.367
[door closes]

44:02.117 --> 44:03.945
Charlie.
I wasn't expecting you.

44:03.989 --> 44:06.992
I just got in.
You're my first stop.

44:13.172 --> 44:14.564
You're a pain
in the ass, Ruddy,

44:14.608 --> 44:17.872
but you've done a good job
on this movie.

44:17.916 --> 44:19.744
Thank you.Yeah.

44:25.793 --> 44:27.969
Evans is done.

44:28.013 --> 44:29.623
I wanted you
to hear it from me.

44:31.277 --> 44:34.193
This isn't easy for me,
whatever you think.

44:35.890 --> 44:37.762
But it has to be done.

44:37.805 --> 44:41.069
And I'm putting Lapidus
in charge.

44:41.113 --> 44:44.290
Charlie, we need Bob.

44:44.333 --> 44:45.857
You know that we do.

44:49.077 --> 44:51.471
This whiskey
tastes like shit.

44:51.514 --> 44:53.429
Get something that burns.

45:08.183 --> 45:10.142
We're going to go
with this one,

45:10.185 --> 45:12.057
but let's use
the other tagline--

45:12.100 --> 45:15.103
"Take the Cannoli."That's great.

45:15.147 --> 45:16.931
Charlie, what do you think?

45:16.975 --> 45:19.325
Just observing.

45:19.368 --> 45:21.762
And, Francis, thank you for
trimming the fat off the movie.

45:21.806 --> 45:24.417
It's much better now.Yeah, stayed awake this time.

45:24.460 --> 45:26.462
FRANCIS:
Shorter is not always better.

45:26.506 --> 45:29.378
Charlie, you really should
consider the longer cut.

45:29.422 --> 45:31.641
It is better.BARRY: For who? Hmm?

45:31.685 --> 45:33.252
Your ego?

45:33.295 --> 45:34.862
I thought I explained
the business to you, Ruddy.

45:34.906 --> 45:37.212
BOB:
The audience doesn't care

45:37.256 --> 45:40.085
about our business, Barry.

45:40.128 --> 45:41.477
Bob.

45:44.132 --> 45:45.743
How's the back?

45:45.786 --> 45:47.266
Getting there.
Thanks for asking.

45:48.528 --> 45:49.834
Flying V?

45:53.185 --> 45:54.795
We can't use this.

45:54.839 --> 45:57.885
You can't just show up here
whenever you want

45:57.929 --> 45:59.757
and just blow apart
everything we're working on.

45:59.800 --> 46:01.628
I'm not blowing
anything up, Barry.

46:01.671 --> 46:03.891
It simply does not represent
the film.

46:03.935 --> 46:06.981
It doesn't create mystery
or intrigue.

46:07.025 --> 46:09.114
That's your opinion, Bob.You're damn right it is.

46:09.157 --> 46:10.724
But it's also based on
market research as well.

46:10.768 --> 46:12.770
Our testing has shown

46:12.813 --> 46:15.555
that audiences are turned off
by busy key art.

46:15.598 --> 46:18.819
They particularly don't like
the V.

46:18.863 --> 46:20.647
It doesn't allow them
to connect to anything.

46:20.690 --> 46:22.475
Look, "The Godfather" sold
more copies

46:22.518 --> 46:24.477
than any other book in history
except for the Bible.

46:24.520 --> 46:26.087
Now, we're trying to take
the audience

46:26.131 --> 46:28.002
for a peek inside
the secretive subculture

46:28.046 --> 46:29.308
they're not normally privy to.

46:29.351 --> 46:32.137
We should be using
the key art

46:32.180 --> 46:35.314
from the book.

46:35.357 --> 46:36.881
It creates mystery.

46:38.665 --> 46:40.449
What about the cut?I'm glad you asked.

46:40.493 --> 46:41.624
'Cause as far as I remember,

46:41.668 --> 46:43.322
we hired Francis
to make us a movie.

46:43.365 --> 46:46.194
And the shorter version
of this film, it's a trailer.

46:46.238 --> 46:48.501
It's a teaser.
It's a--it's an insult.

46:48.544 --> 46:49.850
It is defeat

46:49.894 --> 46:51.809
waiting to be pulled
from the jaws of victory.

46:51.852 --> 46:55.421
And, Francis, frankly,
your cut is gorgeous.

46:55.464 --> 46:56.726
Sublime. Perfect.

46:56.770 --> 46:58.641
Bob, you know
as well as I do

46:58.685 --> 47:00.121
that, one,
it's going to reduce

47:00.165 --> 47:01.644
the number of screenings
per day.

47:01.688 --> 47:04.082
And, two, no one wants
to sit in a theater that long

47:04.125 --> 47:05.300
for a gangster movie.

47:05.344 --> 47:06.649
Yeah, I do know that,

47:06.693 --> 47:08.129
but this is not
a typical gangster movie.

47:08.173 --> 47:09.478
It never was,
and we're not offering

47:09.522 --> 47:11.567
the audience a transaction.

47:11.611 --> 47:14.309
We're offering them
an experience.

47:14.353 --> 47:17.312
Look, we need to evolve
with the population.

47:17.356 --> 47:20.838
We need to lead the revolution,
or it will pass us by, Charlie.

47:22.796 --> 47:24.754
Barry...

47:24.798 --> 47:26.756
you never wanted to make
"Rosemary's Baby"

47:26.800 --> 47:28.149
or "Love Story."

47:28.193 --> 47:29.498
You didn't want to make
"The Godfather."

47:29.542 --> 47:31.805
These--these movies,
they break all the rules.

47:31.849 --> 47:33.981
They're not formulaic.

47:34.025 --> 47:35.287
This is part of why they work.

47:35.330 --> 47:36.723
But, look, we can't chase

47:36.766 --> 47:38.290
after what we think an audience
wants to see.

47:38.333 --> 47:40.074
We got to show the audience
what it needs to see.

47:43.382 --> 47:45.514
How did you get
the cuts, Bob, huh?

47:47.952 --> 47:49.127
Bubbe, please.

47:55.873 --> 47:57.918
Let me think about it.

47:57.962 --> 47:59.137
Everybody out.

47:59.180 --> 48:00.442
Barry, you stay.

48:00.486 --> 48:03.402
[soft dramatic music]

48:03.445 --> 48:10.452
♪

48:10.496 --> 48:13.151
RUDDY: All right.
How do you think that went?

48:13.194 --> 48:15.196
BART: [scoffs]
Hard to tell.

48:17.111 --> 48:19.766
Bob, what does this mean?

48:19.809 --> 48:21.115
Can we go back
to the longer cut?

48:21.159 --> 48:23.378
Oh, God, I hope so.

48:23.422 --> 48:25.641
I really loved it, Francis.

48:25.685 --> 48:27.339
You did it, man.

48:27.382 --> 48:28.296
Thank you.

48:28.340 --> 48:29.819
One thing--

48:29.863 --> 48:31.082
horse's head scene,

48:31.125 --> 48:33.606
the music gets too ominous
too quickly.

48:33.649 --> 48:35.260
It gives away
what's about to happen.

48:35.303 --> 48:37.436
Why don't you
take a look at that?

48:39.568 --> 48:40.918
Is that it?

48:40.961 --> 48:41.962
For now.

48:42.006 --> 48:44.225
[laughs] Okay.

48:44.269 --> 48:45.574
It's good
to have you back, boss.

48:45.618 --> 48:47.620
Yeah, we'll see.

48:47.663 --> 48:49.665
Go on. Get out of here.[chuckles]

48:49.709 --> 48:51.015
Go on.

48:56.934 --> 48:59.284
You still want it?

48:59.327 --> 49:00.546
What?

49:04.985 --> 49:06.247
And Evans?

49:06.291 --> 49:08.249
That would be your decision.

49:16.040 --> 49:18.651
He's a pain in the ass.

49:18.694 --> 49:21.915
He's egotistical, smug,
and entitled.

49:24.613 --> 49:26.441
We've never gotten along.

49:26.485 --> 49:28.835
We agree on nothing,
and if it were up to me,

49:28.878 --> 49:31.664
I would've been the first one
to get him a one-way ticket

49:31.707 --> 49:33.274
to anywhere but here.

49:35.929 --> 49:37.800
And I would've been wrong.

49:40.325 --> 49:43.502
He's still an asshole,
but there's no denying talent.

49:43.545 --> 49:46.026
And despite all
of his posturing and bullshit,

49:46.070 --> 49:47.941
he's got good instincts.

49:49.551 --> 49:51.727
A lot of what he touches
turns to gold.

49:53.642 --> 49:55.079
That's what's important.

49:57.646 --> 50:00.214
Are you saying you--Evans should be at the helm.

50:00.258 --> 50:03.174
[soft dramatic music]

50:03.217 --> 50:05.611
♪

50:05.654 --> 50:07.091
You surprise me, Barry.

50:10.094 --> 50:12.400
Yeah, well...
[clears throat]

50:12.444 --> 50:14.228
Never hate your enemies.

50:14.272 --> 50:16.752
It's not personal.

50:16.796 --> 50:18.885
It's just business.
[scoffs]

50:21.409 --> 50:22.758
Hmm.

50:22.802 --> 50:29.722
♪

50:38.209 --> 50:40.602
How do I know
I can trust you?

50:43.040 --> 50:45.912
I don't know, Charlie.

50:45.955 --> 50:48.045
I only have my word.

51:00.927 --> 51:03.582
I like movies
about history.

51:03.625 --> 51:06.106
Did you know that?

51:06.150 --> 51:08.978
I did not.
Mm.

51:09.022 --> 51:11.633
Yeah, sure, I like all the tits
and the action

51:11.677 --> 51:14.854
and all the rest,
but history...

51:14.897 --> 51:18.466
we get to see something which
is impossible for us to see,

51:18.510 --> 51:23.341
and the story is retold to be
whatever we want it to be.

51:23.384 --> 51:25.821
Some people think
that's a crime,

51:25.865 --> 51:28.433
but I don't.

51:28.476 --> 51:30.391
Rewriting history...

51:32.828 --> 51:35.440
Maybe that's how we can deal
with the horror.

51:39.183 --> 51:41.968
If you could rewrite
your history, would you?

51:45.145 --> 51:47.800
No.

51:47.843 --> 51:50.759
May not be pretty,
but it's mine.

51:53.980 --> 51:56.025
Smart money says
get rid of you.

51:58.332 --> 51:59.899
I understand.

52:01.944 --> 52:04.033
Barry convinced me otherwise.

52:06.775 --> 52:10.301
You're getting a chance
to rewrite your history, Bob.

52:13.217 --> 52:15.132
Don't make me regret it.

52:15.175 --> 52:18.178
[soft dramatic music]

52:18.222 --> 52:19.397
♪

52:19.440 --> 52:22.313
Now go make me
some fucking money.

52:22.356 --> 52:24.315
[chuckles softly]

52:24.358 --> 52:31.235
♪

52:37.415 --> 52:39.156
[footsteps approaching]

52:39.199 --> 52:41.332
[door opens]

52:41.375 --> 52:43.464
[door closes]

52:43.508 --> 52:45.031
Guess what.

52:45.074 --> 52:46.511
We're going
with the longer cut.

52:46.554 --> 52:48.948
Oh, thank God.

52:48.991 --> 52:50.384
That's great news.

52:50.428 --> 52:52.430
Oh, you think so?

52:52.473 --> 52:53.822
You said you liked
the longer cut.

52:53.866 --> 52:55.302
I meant it.
I meant it.

52:55.346 --> 52:56.651
But don't think for a second

52:56.695 --> 52:58.349
that if this thing
flops financially,

52:58.392 --> 53:00.177
you and I won't end up
being chained to a rock

53:00.220 --> 53:02.527
with Bluhdorn picking
at our livers every day.

53:02.570 --> 53:04.224
Lapidus wasn't wrong.

53:04.268 --> 53:05.834
There are huge risks to doing
it the way we're doing it.

53:05.878 --> 53:07.445
I know, I know.
Less screenings a day.

53:07.488 --> 53:09.186
That's a very big deal.

53:09.229 --> 53:11.100
And even more than that,
with a longer cut,

53:11.144 --> 53:12.841
there's no way
we're ready for Christmas,

53:12.885 --> 53:14.582
which is the best time
to release this movie

53:14.626 --> 53:16.149
or even a month later.

53:16.193 --> 53:18.412
Audience attendances drop
like a fucking brick.

53:18.456 --> 53:21.110
Oh, come on, we got lightning
in a bottle here.

53:21.154 --> 53:22.895
Well, if that bottle's
in your pocket,

53:22.938 --> 53:24.549
be careful you don't fry
your balls with it.

53:24.592 --> 53:25.724
[chuckles]

53:25.767 --> 53:28.205
Look, if it was easy,

53:28.248 --> 53:29.815
everybody would do it.

53:29.858 --> 53:31.295
Amen.

53:34.298 --> 53:37.039
Oh, and, Al...

53:41.043 --> 53:42.828
Thank you.

53:45.439 --> 53:47.180
Anytime, bubbe.

53:47.224 --> 53:50.270
[chuckles]

53:50.314 --> 53:52.272
Yeah.

53:53.621 --> 53:55.406
[door opens]

53:55.449 --> 53:57.843
[soft lounge music playing]

53:57.886 --> 53:59.410
BOB: Oh, yes, I see.
Thank you.

53:59.453 --> 54:01.977
♪

54:02.021 --> 54:04.153
Michael.Hey, Bob.

54:04.197 --> 54:05.503
Hey, Jerry.Hey, Bob.

54:05.546 --> 54:06.895
Eat your food.

54:06.939 --> 54:07.940
Well,
it's a very particular--

54:07.983 --> 54:10.421
He's coming this way.
Um, Bob?

54:10.464 --> 54:17.384
♪

54:25.610 --> 54:27.002
Barry.

54:28.656 --> 54:30.876
Bob.

54:30.919 --> 54:33.400
Mind if I join you?

54:33.444 --> 54:35.620
Please.

54:35.663 --> 54:38.231
[grunts, sighs]

54:38.275 --> 54:41.495
You know, they don't always put
salmon on the menu,

54:41.539 --> 54:43.280
but they'll make it for us.

54:43.323 --> 54:45.325
[chuckles]

54:45.369 --> 54:46.674
Mineral water, Barry?

54:46.718 --> 54:48.807
Yeah.

54:48.850 --> 54:49.895
John.

54:49.938 --> 54:53.115
Thank you for coming in.

54:53.159 --> 54:54.247
Oh.Excuse me.

54:54.291 --> 54:55.248
Hey.

54:57.555 --> 54:59.383
Is that the cigarette ad guy?

55:01.515 --> 55:04.823
I got to be honest, that is
one handsome motherfucker.

55:04.866 --> 55:06.781
So?I've never been so happy

55:06.825 --> 55:09.262
to see that tan bastard
in my life.

55:11.743 --> 55:14.485
Bettye, I need your help.

55:14.528 --> 55:16.835
Could I get fired for it?

55:16.878 --> 55:20.273
We both could,
but it's worth it.

55:20.317 --> 55:23.276
[funky music]

55:23.320 --> 55:26.366
You're not on the list.

55:26.410 --> 55:28.194
Well, that just doesn't make
any sense, Gene.

55:28.237 --> 55:30.022
Eugene.

55:30.065 --> 55:33.068
Eugene.
Of course. Sorry.

55:33.112 --> 55:35.157
It's just you remind me
a lot of Gene Kelly.

55:35.201 --> 55:37.943
You must get that
all the time.

55:37.986 --> 55:39.771
You're not on the list.

55:39.814 --> 55:41.381
Bob Evans sent me.

55:41.425 --> 55:43.949
Call Sheila.
Check it out.

55:43.992 --> 55:45.385
What's your name again?

55:45.429 --> 55:48.475
[sighs]

55:48.519 --> 55:50.042
Be careful.

55:50.085 --> 55:51.957
There's only two prints.Of course.

55:52.000 --> 55:53.698
Thank you, Eugene.

55:53.741 --> 55:55.917
[giggles]

55:57.484 --> 55:59.747
[engine turning over]

55:59.791 --> 56:02.359
♪

56:09.061 --> 56:11.672
[chuckles]
Relax, they're fine.

56:11.716 --> 56:15.110
That is $6.5 million
sitting in that seat.

56:16.938 --> 56:19.463
[chuckles]

56:19.506 --> 56:21.639
How'd you end up
getting the plane?

56:21.682 --> 56:23.292
Bob owed me one.

56:23.336 --> 56:26.339
Mm.Yeah.

56:26.383 --> 56:30.865
So what was up with that
actor meeting the other day?

56:30.909 --> 56:33.390
I was just looking at options
for your next picture.

56:40.527 --> 56:42.703
All right, all right.

56:42.747 --> 56:44.662
[clears throat]

56:46.315 --> 56:49.580
I was thinking
about what I want to do next,

56:49.623 --> 56:51.799
and I'm thinking
of maybe becoming an agent.

56:51.843 --> 56:55.412
[soft piano music]

56:55.455 --> 56:57.892
What?
You don't think I can do it?

56:57.936 --> 57:00.591
No, no.
I think you can do anything.

57:02.027 --> 57:03.332
What is it, then?

57:03.376 --> 57:06.423
♪

57:06.466 --> 57:09.295
I don't know.
I guess...

57:09.338 --> 57:11.123
when I think
about what's next,

57:11.166 --> 57:13.386
I just assumed
you'd be there with me.

57:14.866 --> 57:16.955
I love working for you, Al.

57:19.436 --> 57:21.002
But I do want more.

57:21.046 --> 57:23.309
I mean, when the world looks
at me, all they see is someone

57:23.352 --> 57:25.833
whose job it is
to support a man.

57:29.402 --> 57:30.577
Why an agent?

57:32.274 --> 57:34.363
I really like actors.

57:34.407 --> 57:36.801
I mean, they're delusional--
they have to be

57:36.844 --> 57:39.194
if they think they're gonna
make it in this business.

57:39.238 --> 57:42.197
And justified or not,
they all dream big.

57:42.241 --> 57:43.851
Also, I am loud.
Mm.

57:43.895 --> 57:45.374
I am very smart.Mm.

57:45.418 --> 57:48.421
[chuckles]
I'm vicious.

57:48.465 --> 57:51.380
I mean,
maybe I'm delusional, too.

57:51.424 --> 57:53.208
But I do know

57:53.252 --> 57:56.516
that I don't want to get
trapped in this tiny little box

57:56.560 --> 57:59.214
that the men of this world
have given me.

57:59.258 --> 58:01.347
I want my own seat
at the table.

58:01.390 --> 58:08.310
♪

58:10.356 --> 58:13.228
[indistinct chatter]

58:15.274 --> 58:16.405
Hey, get up.

58:16.449 --> 58:18.059
Hi.

58:18.103 --> 58:19.931
Hey.

58:19.974 --> 58:22.890
They didn't have Raisinettes.No.

58:22.934 --> 58:24.457
What about Whoppers?

58:24.501 --> 58:25.589
She wants Whoppers, okay.

58:25.632 --> 58:27.634
I'm joking.
Sit down.

58:27.678 --> 58:28.896
Is this one mine?Yeah.

58:28.940 --> 58:30.898
Thank you.

58:30.942 --> 58:32.683
I can't believe Paramount

58:32.726 --> 58:34.902
is gonna do this
special screening just for us.

58:41.082 --> 58:43.563
Hey, where did you
just come from?

58:43.607 --> 58:45.347
The alley.

58:45.391 --> 58:46.958
Why?

58:47.001 --> 58:49.700
Because every gangster
within 50 miles is in here,

58:49.743 --> 58:51.702
which means
the FBI is out there.

58:51.745 --> 58:54.139
And I for once would like
to remain anonymous.

58:54.182 --> 58:55.836
PERSON: Hey, Ruddy!

58:55.880 --> 58:58.317
If this movie sucks, you ain't
making it out of the theater.

58:58.360 --> 59:01.233
[laughter]

59:01.276 --> 59:05.063
And he fucking means it, too![laughter]

59:08.240 --> 59:09.981
[solo trumpet playing]

59:10.024 --> 59:11.983
[person shushes]

59:12.026 --> 59:18.946
♪

59:22.471 --> 59:27.085
[cheers and applause]

59:27.128 --> 59:28.826
Awoo!

59:28.869 --> 59:32.438
[cheers and applause continue]

59:32.481 --> 59:39.358
♪

59:45.669 --> 59:48.585
[dramatic music]

59:48.628 --> 59:50.630
ALL: Oh!

59:50.674 --> 59:51.979
PERSON: Ruddy!

59:52.023 --> 59:54.982
[soft laughter]

59:55.026 --> 59:57.942
[dramatic music builds]

59:57.985 --> 59:59.639
[explosion]

59:59.683 --> 1:00:02.337
[audience gasping]

1:00:02.381 --> 1:00:05.297
[music mellows]

1:00:05.340 --> 1:00:12.260
♪

1:00:27.711 --> 1:00:29.713
PERSON ON SCREEN:
Don Corleone...

1:00:31.062 --> 1:00:34.413
[projector clicks]

1:00:34.456 --> 1:00:39.200
[cheers and applause]

1:00:41.812 --> 1:00:44.075
I guess we live
to see another day!

1:00:44.118 --> 1:00:46.599
What a relief.[laughs]

1:00:46.643 --> 1:00:48.035
Look at this!

1:00:48.079 --> 1:00:50.255
Wow.

1:00:50.298 --> 1:00:52.953
Oh, my God.

1:00:52.997 --> 1:00:56.435
I think that might be
the best movie I've ever seen.

1:00:56.478 --> 1:00:58.263
That means a lot.

1:00:58.306 --> 1:01:00.395
Honestly, I think we care more
about what you guys think

1:01:00.439 --> 1:01:02.441
than anybody else.

1:01:02.484 --> 1:01:05.052
The boss would've loved it.

1:01:08.752 --> 1:01:10.188
Do me a favor.

1:01:10.231 --> 1:01:12.016
Grab the print, catch a cab
back to the hotel.

1:01:12.059 --> 1:01:14.192
I got to go do something.Of course.

1:01:18.805 --> 1:01:19.980
Hey.

1:01:22.853 --> 1:01:25.551
Listen, I'd really like
to take you out

1:01:25.594 --> 1:01:28.510
the next time
you're back in New York.

1:01:28.554 --> 1:01:30.425
I don't know, Caesar.

1:01:32.471 --> 1:01:34.995
You're a pretty dangerous guy.
[chuckles]

1:01:35.039 --> 1:01:37.650
Um, some girls like
dangerous.

1:01:37.694 --> 1:01:40.566
[soft dramatic music]

1:01:40.609 --> 1:01:47.529
♪

1:01:50.097 --> 1:01:52.970
[monitor beeping quietly]

1:01:56.103 --> 1:02:02.980
♪

1:02:08.159 --> 1:02:09.464
They, uh--

1:02:11.597 --> 1:02:14.078
They all stood up
and applauded, Joe.

1:02:14.121 --> 1:02:15.819
[chuckles]

1:02:15.862 --> 1:02:17.734
You would've loved it.

1:02:25.437 --> 1:02:27.221
Tell you what, buddy.

1:02:29.397 --> 1:02:30.572
When you're feeling better,

1:02:30.616 --> 1:02:33.445
I'm gonna set up
a special screening

1:02:33.488 --> 1:02:35.316
just for you.

1:02:35.360 --> 1:02:40.757
♪

1:02:40.757 --> 1:02:45.370
♪

1:04:21.553 --> 1:04:23.033
AL: We've got a great movie.

1:04:23.076 --> 1:04:25.818
It doesn't matter
if nobody sees it.

1:04:25.862 --> 1:04:27.254
We gotta do
something different here.

1:04:27.298 --> 1:04:27.951
Like what?

1:04:29.126 --> 1:04:31.476
We need to get something going,
and fast.

1:04:31.911 --> 1:04:34.131
It's crazy.Crazy's good, I like crazy.

1:04:34.174 --> 1:04:35.349
That's unheard of.

1:04:35.393 --> 1:04:36.698
BARRY:
It's never been done before.

1:04:36.742 --> 1:04:38.744
Why play it safe
when we can crash and burn.

1:04:38.787 --> 1:04:41.181
The idea of losing money
gives me a rash.

1:04:41.225 --> 1:04:42.269
But if it works...

1:04:42.313 --> 1:04:43.749
Do you think I'm crazy
for doing this?

1:04:44.271 --> 1:04:45.838
...we make film history.

1:04:48.319 --> 1:04:51.061
ROBERT: I have this
recurring dream
aboutThe Godfather premiere.

1:04:51.104 --> 1:04:51.888
Wow.

1:04:53.672 --> 1:04:54.978
ROBERT: It's the pot of gold
at the end of the rainbow.

1:04:55.021 --> 1:04:58.677
And it's a perfect night.
To The Godfather.

1:05:08.078 --> 1:05:08.948
DIRECTOR: Action.

1:05:15.346 --> 1:05:17.652
Barry, when did you get in?

1:05:17.957 --> 1:05:18.871
Come in.

1:05:20.786 --> 1:05:21.656
Right.

1:05:22.396 --> 1:05:23.354
Close the door.

1:05:24.137 --> 1:05:25.008
Sure.

1:05:27.488 --> 1:05:29.099
I play Barry Lapidus.

1:05:29.142 --> 1:05:31.144
Lapidus is kind of the bad guy.

1:05:31.405 --> 1:05:34.452
He's an antagonist for
a lot of the series.

1:05:34.495 --> 1:05:37.237
He is basically a composite
of every single person

1:05:37.281 --> 1:05:39.544
that did not want to make
The Godfather.

1:05:44.505 --> 1:05:48.161
No, I'm not green-lighting
anything I don't understand.

1:05:48.205 --> 1:05:49.946
All right, we're going
to stop developing

1:05:49.989 --> 1:05:51.730
these rarefied flights of fancy,

1:05:51.773 --> 1:05:54.037
and start applying some
good business sense

1:05:54.080 --> 1:05:55.212
to what we do here.

1:05:56.735 --> 1:05:58.737
Normally, you know, when you
have those kinds of roles,

1:05:58.780 --> 1:06:00.782
it can kind of be
one dimensional.

1:06:01.044 --> 1:06:04.699
But every reason
that Lapidus has

1:06:04.743 --> 1:06:07.572
as to why this is a bad idea,

1:06:07.615 --> 1:06:09.966
from his perspective,
makes perfect sense.

1:06:10.314 --> 1:06:13.839
And money, gentlemen, whether
you care to admit it or not,

1:06:13.882 --> 1:06:14.883
it's important,

1:06:16.059 --> 1:06:17.408
'cause otherwise
movies don't get made.

1:06:17.451 --> 1:06:19.540
If there weren't for the
business side of people

1:06:19.584 --> 1:06:21.020
who did fight for the creatives,

1:06:21.064 --> 1:06:23.327
then it would just
be the business side

1:06:23.370 --> 1:06:24.676
and who knows what
we may have lost

1:06:24.719 --> 1:06:26.112
or what we may have never seen.

1:06:26.504 --> 1:06:28.462
PETER: If you're
stepping into Evans' shoes,

1:06:29.811 --> 1:06:32.249
you need to understand
what he actually does.

1:06:33.076 --> 1:06:34.686
Lapidus was the last character

1:06:34.729 --> 1:06:37.689
I thought I was going
to have empathy for,

1:06:37.732 --> 1:06:40.170
but there's a scene in nine
that Colin does beautifully,

1:06:40.431 --> 1:06:42.781
where he's trying
to kind of take over

1:06:42.824 --> 1:06:44.348
and fill Evans' shoes,

1:06:44.739 --> 1:06:47.873
and there's a moment
where he's sitting

1:06:47.916 --> 1:06:48.830
behind Evans' desk,

1:06:50.354 --> 1:06:51.616
and you're enough in
his head at that point

1:06:51.659 --> 1:06:53.705
that you realize
he's grappling with the thought

1:06:53.748 --> 1:06:55.315
that he does not
have what it takes

1:06:55.359 --> 1:06:58.014
to be what Bob Evans was.

1:06:58.362 --> 1:07:00.059
He realizes that he
doesn't necessarily

1:07:00.103 --> 1:07:01.365
have the skill set for that.

1:07:01.887 --> 1:07:02.757
And to his credit,

1:07:03.932 --> 1:07:05.456
he was smart enough
to recognize that,

1:07:05.499 --> 1:07:08.198
and ends up being a champion
of Evans in the end.

1:07:08.241 --> 1:07:09.721
We agree on nothing,

1:07:09.764 --> 1:07:10.896
and if it were up to me,

1:07:10.939 --> 1:07:12.767
I would've been the
first one to get him

1:07:12.811 --> 1:07:15.074
a one way ticket
to anywhere but here.

1:07:17.120 --> 1:07:18.425
And I would've been wrong.

1:07:18.469 --> 1:07:20.166
ADAM: I love that
when characters

1:07:20.210 --> 1:07:22.690
that you have pegged
as being one thing

1:07:22.734 --> 1:07:26.738
suddenly end up having to play
a different and vital role.

1:07:26.781 --> 1:07:27.913
I thought it was a nice touch,

1:07:29.523 --> 1:07:31.656
and it was a nice way to sort
of bring him into the fold,

1:07:31.699 --> 1:07:35.051
as sort of, you know, one of
the quote unquote "good guys".

1:07:36.008 --> 1:07:37.096
You surprise me, Barry.

1:07:38.532 --> 1:07:42.754
There's a lot of
things in the original Godfather

1:07:42.797 --> 1:07:45.539
that, they've
become iconic lines.

1:07:45.887 --> 1:07:49.674
Yeah, well, never
hate your enemies.

1:07:50.153 --> 1:07:51.197
It's not personal.

1:07:52.503 --> 1:07:53.547
It's just business.

1:07:55.071 --> 1:07:56.333
COLIN: We are able
to slip those things in,

1:07:56.376 --> 1:07:58.422
and hopefully it's
something that, you know,

1:07:58.465 --> 1:08:01.555
fans of the film will
sort of get the reference.

1:08:01.947 --> 1:08:05.124
Making a reference
to The Godfather,

1:08:05.168 --> 1:08:08.693
I feel like I've been doing
that my entire career.

1:08:09.694 --> 1:08:12.392
There were, you know,
sort of winks and nods

1:08:12.436 --> 1:08:13.393
and Easter eggs.

1:08:14.786 --> 1:08:16.788
The intention of
the Easter eggs in The Offer

1:08:17.310 --> 1:08:20.226
was meant to draw a parallel

1:08:20.270 --> 1:08:25.057
between the story in the film
and the story of the film.

1:08:25.536 --> 1:08:27.059
[HEART MONITOR BEEPS]

1:08:27.103 --> 1:08:28.974
It's the final
scene of Episode 9.

1:08:29.017 --> 1:08:31.759
Colombo's unconscious,
still sedated.

1:08:32.108 --> 1:08:34.197
The final moment of the scene

1:08:34.240 --> 1:08:38.114
is Al kissing
the hand of Colombo.

1:08:39.724 --> 1:08:41.682
I wanted to compose a shot

1:08:42.118 --> 1:08:45.164
that echoed the final shot
in the film ofThe Godfather,

1:08:45.208 --> 1:08:48.080
where Kay is in
the foreground out of focus,

1:08:48.298 --> 1:08:50.648
and you see back into the room,

1:08:50.691 --> 1:08:52.128
and before the door closes,

1:08:52.171 --> 1:08:53.781
you see Clemenza kiss his hand.

1:08:53.825 --> 1:08:56.175
Colombo is a real
friendship for him.

1:08:56.523 --> 1:08:59.483
I developed a great
relationship with this man.

1:08:59.787 --> 1:09:01.180
And without Colombo's help,

1:09:01.224 --> 1:09:02.660
he never could have
got this movie made.

1:09:02.703 --> 1:09:04.488
I genuinely respected him.

1:09:04.531 --> 1:09:08.405
We became lasting
friends for a long time.

1:09:08.448 --> 1:09:09.667
He pays homage.

1:09:09.710 --> 1:09:12.017
This really is one
of his godfathers,

1:09:12.060 --> 1:09:13.192
and maybe the biggest one.
